Project Topic¶

This project is about if, after the COVID-19 pandemic, people prefer working from home or working from the office. This data set is survey data tabulated to determine whether people prefer working from home and do the demographics of these people surveyed impact their preference. The ages, occupation, gender, whether they have kids or not, and where their office is located inside their residence are features that are documented. Some of the questions asked are whether they though staying home saved money, improved sleep, increased or decreased productivity, or improved work/life balance.

The machine learning task I will be using is classification to be able to determine which groups of people would rather work from home or work in office and what benefits or detriments it provided.

Project Goal¶

My goal for this project is to determine if there are any benefits to working from home compared to working in the office. Or if there are any downfalls to working from home. This is important because after the COVID-19 pandemic the amount of people working from home increased by a large amount. In 2023 companies are now discussing returning back to the office or doing a hybrid work environment where some work days are in office and some are from home. With this push to return back to office will there be a loss of benefits that people were reeping when they worked from home?

Data¶

This data set is survey data from kaggle. Hardly any machine learning tasks or data analysis has been done on this data set so there is a lot of information that can be discovered. A bit about the specifics of the data set is discussed in the project topic. Citation: anninasimon. (n.d.). Predict If People Prefer WFH Versus WFO Data. Retrieved from https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/anninasimon/predict-if-people-prefer-wfh-verses-wfo-data

Data Cleaning¶

Data cleaning is important because data cleaning ensures the accuracy and reliability of the data. Unclean data contains errors, outliers, null values and inconsistencies that will effect the machine learning model predictions and data analysis. Without data cleaning we are unable to provide high-quality insights about the model predictions. Data cleaning also makes the data easier to deal with. Removing irrelevant features to your analysis can help narrow focus down to what is necessary for more accurate results so that we do not get bogged down with too much information.

There are no null values in this data set, if there were I would remove them since the data is so small and imputing values may cause outliers or incorrect informaiton.

I will start by removing feature columns from the data set that I am not going to include in my modeling or analysis.

I am also going to remove features that are highly correlated with one another because the data will become too redundant and interfere with analysis and machine learning modeling

Modeling¶

Logistic Regresion¶

I chose to do logistic regression to model to predict if an individual would choose to work from home or work from the office based on the attributes. Logistic regression works well for this data set because it is usually used for binary classification/ prediction. Binary classification has 2 outcome. The binary outcomes for this data set are either 'Yes' or 'No'. Yes meaning the individual would rather work from home and no being the individual would rather work from office. There are other modeling methods that could be used but since logistical regression produces a high accuracy for this model, is typically used for binary classification and is efficient, quick and flexible. Since logistic regression it flexible it can produce higher accuracy.

Step 1: map data into 1 for yes and 0 for no so that logistic regression can perform correctly. Also mapping the categorical data variables to 1 and 0.

# mapping the yes and no columns to 1 and 0. 
# categorical variable columns with yes or no values 
categorical = ["RM_save_money", "RM_quality_time", "RM_better_sleep"]

# changing yes to 1 and no to 0
def binary_map(x):
    return x.map({'Yes': 1, 'No': 0, np.nan: -1, 'Unknown': -1})

# replace the values in my data set to 1 and 0 
data_mapped[categorical]=data_mapped[categorical].apply(binary_map)

Based on the usage of logistic regression it seems to fit this data set the best. But, since logistic regression has no hyperparameters I am going to also create a k-nearest neighbors model and see which one performs the best in the results and analysis section.

K-nearest neighbors¶

I am going to be looking at hyperparameters of n_neighbor value to determine how many k-neighbors produces the best accuracy for the model.

I am going to first create a grid search to see which hyperparameters create the best performance for my knn model. This is a way to perform cross-validation for regularization of my model.

In [147]:
knn=KNeighborsClassifier()
#setting paramater values 
param_grid = {
    'n_neighbors': [3, 5, 7],  # Different values of k
    'weights': ['uniform', 'distance'],  # Weighting scheme for neighbors
    'p': [1, 2]  # Distance metric (1: Manhattan, 2: Euclidean)
}

# performing grid search
grid_search = GridSearchCV(knn, param_grid, cv=5)
grid_search.fit(X_train, y_train)

# getting the best hyperparameters 
best_params = grid_search.best_params_
print("Best Hyperparameters:", best_params)
           
        

Best Hyperparameters: {'n_neighbors': 3, 'p': 1, 'weights': 'distance'}

I will now fit my model using 3 for the value of k, Manhattan distance metric and distance weighting scheme for neighbors

In [150]:

Summary of Results¶

The k-nearest neighbors model performed better than the logistic regression model in all measured metrics. The k-nearest neighbors had a model accuracy of about 95% where as the logistic regression model had an accuracy of about 81%. For RMSE, MSE and mean absolute error the k-nearest neighbors model had lower error for all of these values indicating there is less error in the model compared to the logistic regression model, another measure of better performance.

The k-nearest neighbors model also had a higher precision value, recall value and f1-score. In all data metrics the k-nearest neighbors model performs better than the logistic regression model.

Discussion and Conclusion¶

  1. Learnings/Takeaways Throughout this project I learned the importance of creating multiple models with multiple parameters. My original plan was to just do a logistic regression model because it the baseline model for binary classification. After performing a k-nearest neighbors model and using a cross validation to determine the best hyperparameters I found that the k-nearest neighbors model performed significantly better.

I discussed a lot of the results throughout data cleaning, EDA, and modeling. The data cleaning took more time than anticipated, everytime I thought I had the data clean and error would occur and I realized I needed to go back and add more to the cleaning. I tried to do the machine learning modeling without converting my data types into int and the 'Yes' and 'No' of the binary classifiers to map to 1 and 0. Without this the model would not have created any results.

  1. Why somethings didn't work The modeling I used worked decently well but one could argue that the logistic regression model did not have a high enough accuracy score at about 81% which is a lot of missclassifications for a data set this size to say it performed well.
  1. Suggested Improvements I would try out different machine learning models like a Decision Tree or Support Vector Machines (SVM) to see if these would have a better performance than k-nearest neighnbors. Also including more of the attributes in the model not just ones I found of interest could improve the accuracy of the model or more so the interpretation of the results.
